00:10:36.792 --> 00:10:38.165 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah, it is.

00:10:38.165 --> 00:10:39.850 align:middle line:84%
And not only that,
these poor kids

00:10:39.850 --> 00:10:44.150 align:middle line:84%
are struggling to even find a
means of supporting themselves.

00:10:44.150 --> 00:10:45.970 align:middle line:84%
It's not the world
that we inherited.

00:10:45.970 --> 00:10:47.710 align:middle line:90%
Theirs is a depleted world.

00:10:47.710 --> 00:10:49.690 align:middle line:84%
>>ZEUS: Exactly,
and it's depleted

00:10:49.690 --> 00:10:53.080 align:middle line:84%
because, much like a cancer,
all of the available resources

00:10:53.080 --> 00:10:55.430 align:middle line:84%
are being sucked into
the multiplication

00:10:55.430 --> 00:10:59.200 align:middle line:84%
of a particular segment
of the population that

00:10:59.200 --> 00:11:02.640 align:middle line:84%
is only interested in expanding
and concentrating wealth

00:11:02.640 --> 00:11:07.700 align:middle line:84%
and the results of productivity
in their own lives.

00:11:07.700 --> 00:11:11.160 align:middle line:84%
And no healthy system
operates that way.

00:11:11.160 --> 00:11:13.370 align:middle line:84%
Healthy systems
always have diversity.

00:11:13.370 --> 00:11:14.990 align:middle line:90%
They have exchange.

00:11:14.990 --> 00:11:17.950 align:middle line:84%
They have sharing,
in a word, sharing.

00:11:17.950 --> 00:11:21.250 align:middle line:84%
And when you have taking
motivating everything,

00:11:21.250 --> 00:11:24.310 align:middle line:84%
you always go toward
death, death of a system.

00:11:24.310 --> 00:11:27.170 align:middle line:84%
Now death doesn't have
to be a bad thing, right?

00:11:27.170 --> 00:11:30.250 align:middle line:90%


00:11:30.250 --> 00:11:31.950 align:middle line:84%
Bad systems can
undermine themselves,

00:11:31.950 --> 00:11:34.770 align:middle line:84%
but we need a healthy
response to that system.

00:11:34.770 --> 00:11:36.550 align:middle line:84%
And right now,
we're in the middle

00:11:36.550 --> 00:11:41.920 align:middle line:84%
of recognizing that this is in
no way sustainable or healthy.

00:11:41.920 --> 00:11:47.250 align:middle line:84%
So that's what partly motivated
this top 10 most outrageous

00:11:47.250 --> 00:11:50.770 align:middle line:84%
list because I want people
to really be able to focus in

00:11:50.770 --> 00:11:52.710 align:middle line:90%
on how we got here.

00:11:52.710 --> 00:11:53.870 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: I totally agree.

00:11:53.870 --> 00:11:56.380 align:middle line:84%
I mean, yeah, this is
the unpleasantness of it,

00:11:56.380 --> 00:11:59.000 align:middle line:84%
but then we're going to get
into the other part after.

00:11:59.000 --> 00:12:03.310 align:middle line:84%
OK, so number nine,
which is rehypothecation,

00:12:03.310 --> 00:12:05.350 align:middle line:84%
and it's using the
same collateral

00:12:05.350 --> 00:12:06.830 align:middle line:90%
for different transactions.

00:12:06.830 --> 00:12:09.050 align:middle line:84%
Tell us what that means
and what would happen if we

00:12:09.050 --> 00:12:10.800 align:middle line:90%
tried to do that in our lives.

00:12:10.800 --> 00:12:13.600 align:middle line:84%
>>ZEUS: Absolutely, let's
say you had a house,

00:12:13.600 --> 00:12:16.290 align:middle line:84%
and you had the ability to
use that house as collateral

00:12:16.290 --> 00:12:17.506 align:middle line:90%
to buy 100 houses.

00:12:17.506 --> 00:12:20.830 align:middle line:90%


00:12:20.830 --> 00:12:23.090 align:middle line:84%
And the banks actually
went for it, right?

00:12:23.090 --> 00:12:28.400 align:middle line:84%
So you have every incentive
to make outrageous risks

00:12:28.400 --> 00:12:32.310 align:middle line:84%
in a whole bunch of different
housing markets on the hope

00:12:32.310 --> 00:12:35.680 align:middle line:84%
that one of them turns up
to have increased its value.

00:12:35.680 --> 00:12:37.710 align:middle line:84%
And then you cash
out, and you get.

00:12:37.710 --> 00:12:39.490 align:middle line:84%
Now on all the other
houses that you've

00:12:39.490 --> 00:12:42.190 align:middle line:84%
used your house as collateral
for, let's say half of them

00:12:42.190 --> 00:12:45.490 align:middle line:84%
went down and only
10 of them went up.

00:12:45.490 --> 00:12:47.700 align:middle line:84%
Then you can just
sort of default

00:12:47.700 --> 00:12:49.011 align:middle line:90%
on all those other ones.

00:12:49.011 --> 00:12:50.510 align:middle line:84%
You can default on
your house, which

00:12:50.510 --> 00:12:52.380 align:middle line:84%
is the only collateral
you put up with,

00:12:52.380 --> 00:12:55.860 align:middle line:84%
and now the banks have to
fight over that collateral.

00:12:55.860 --> 00:13:00.100 align:middle line:84%
And it can't pay for nearly
all of the losses that

00:13:00.100 --> 00:13:01.240 align:middle line:90%
are generated.

00:13:01.240 --> 00:13:05.160 align:middle line:84%
Unfortunately, in
finance that has

00:13:05.160 --> 00:13:08.990 align:middle line:84%
been standard practice with
these financial industries.

00:13:08.990 --> 00:13:11.370 align:middle line:84%
They will use the
same-- and again, it's

00:13:11.370 --> 00:13:15.400 align:middle line:84%
hidden behind these allegedly
complex financial schemes

00:13:15.400 --> 00:13:16.330 align:middle line:90%
and derivatives.

00:13:16.330 --> 00:13:19.180 align:middle line:84%
But they basically are
using the same collateral.

00:13:19.180 --> 00:13:20.430 align:middle line:90%
It's just much like a house.

00:13:20.430 --> 00:13:22.410 align:middle line:84%
They might call it
an asset, or they

00:13:22.410 --> 00:13:27.190 align:middle line:84%
might say, a small reserve, but
a very small reserve in a bank

00:13:27.190 --> 00:13:28.010 align:middle line:90%
account.

00:13:28.010 --> 00:13:31.510 align:middle line:84%
And then they will just
simply leverage that and say,

00:13:31.510 --> 00:13:33.890 align:middle line:84%
you know, it counts for all
these other investments.

00:13:33.890 --> 00:13:37.520 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Right, right,
it should be illegal.

00:13:37.520 --> 00:13:42.080 align:middle line:84%
So if we go to the bank, and
we want to, say, take out

00:13:42.080 --> 00:13:46.070 align:middle line:84%
a loan for a car,
and maybe they're

00:13:46.070 --> 00:13:48.580 align:middle line:84%
looking sideways at you
a bit because you've

00:13:48.580 --> 00:13:51.640 align:middle line:84%
had a little ding on your credit
rating somewhere along the way,

00:13:51.640 --> 00:13:53.870 align:middle line:84%
then you have to
put up collateral,

00:13:53.870 --> 00:13:56.340 align:middle line:84%
something significant
which they will

00:13:56.340 --> 00:13:59.950 align:middle line:84%
come and take away from you if
you start missing a payment.

00:13:59.950 --> 00:14:02.060 align:middle line:84%
So that's how they
work on our end.

00:14:02.060 --> 00:14:04.130 align:middle line:84%
How they work on
their end is just

00:14:04.130 --> 00:14:05.640 align:middle line:90%
sort of criminal in that sense.

00:14:05.640 --> 00:14:09.754 align:middle line:84%
>>ZEUS: Right, because
they did these practices.

00:14:09.754 --> 00:14:11.420 align:middle line:84%
And I don't want to
get ahead of myself,

00:14:11.420 --> 00:14:12.980 align:middle line:84%
so I won't get into
the rest of the list.

00:14:12.980 --> 00:14:15.590 align:middle line:84%
But they did these practices,
and there were no consequences.

00:14:15.590 --> 00:14:18.680 align:middle line:84%
There has not been a
significant investigation,

00:14:18.680 --> 00:14:23.840 align:middle line:84%
much less prosecution, of any
significance to any company.

00:14:23.840 --> 00:14:26.100 align:middle line:84%
They have a couple of bad
apples that they pulled out,

00:14:26.100 --> 00:14:27.490 align:middle line:90%
and even those were very few.

00:14:27.490 --> 00:14:30.570 align:middle line:84%
And they had to be ridiculous,
like Bernie Madoff--

00:14:30.570 --> 00:14:32.770 align:middle line:90%
no accountability, zero.

00:14:32.770 --> 00:14:34.360 align:middle line:84%
And that's what's
causing the outrage,

00:14:34.360 --> 00:14:37.210 align:middle line:84%
both in terms of left and
right political spectrum,

00:14:37.210 --> 00:14:38.550 align:middle line:90%
across the spectrum.

00:14:38.550 --> 00:14:42.670 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Yes, OK, number
eight, fractional reserve, poof,

00:14:42.670 --> 00:14:44.610 align:middle line:90%
the magical money multiplier.

00:14:44.610 --> 00:14:47.640 align:middle line:84%
>>ZEUS: Yeah, well, a lot
of people don't know this,

00:14:47.640 --> 00:14:51.070 align:middle line:84%
but your bank can
basically fabricate money.

00:14:51.070 --> 00:14:53.100 align:middle line:84%
All it needs is a
tenth of a reserve,

00:14:53.100 --> 00:14:54.440 align:middle line:90%
and it can write loans.

00:14:54.440 --> 00:14:58.970 align:middle line:84%
If it has $100,000, it can
write loans for $1 million.

00:14:58.970 --> 00:15:02.730 align:middle line:84%
It can basically multiply
its money by a factor of 10--

00:15:02.730 --> 00:15:05.580 align:middle line:84%
and it's allowed to
do this-- in order

00:15:05.580 --> 00:15:07.206 align:middle line:84%
to, in quotes,
"increase money supply."

00:15:07.206 --> 00:15:08.746 align:middle line:84%
But it's not increasing
money supply.

00:15:08.746 --> 00:15:11.210 align:middle line:84%
It's increasing debt supply
because it's not real money.

00:15:11.210 --> 00:15:14.070 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Exactly, yeah, and
they charge interest on that

00:15:14.070 --> 00:15:14.210 align:middle line:90%
money that they--

00:15:14.210 --> 00:15:16.001 align:middle line:84%
>>ZEUS: Of course they
do, the funny money.

00:15:16.001 --> 00:15:18.256 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: --loan out.

00:15:18.256 --> 00:15:19.630 align:middle line:84%
And that one, I
think, is the one

00:15:19.630 --> 00:15:24.420 align:middle line:84%
that people are most familiar
with, that particular one-- OK,

00:15:24.420 --> 00:15:28.620 align:middle line:84%
this one, mark to model or
mark to fantasy accounting.

00:15:28.620 --> 00:15:30.490 align:middle line:84%
>>ZEUS: Right, this
is another one.

00:15:30.490 --> 00:15:32.960 align:middle line:84%
I mean, again, this is where
this alleged complexity comes

00:15:32.960 --> 00:15:33.760 align:middle line:90%
in.

00:15:33.760 --> 00:15:35.210 align:middle line:90%
It's a very simple con game.

00:15:35.210 --> 00:15:36.790 align:middle line:90%
OK, listen.

00:15:36.790 --> 00:15:41.800 align:middle line:84%
If I want to
leverage what I have,

00:15:41.800 --> 00:15:44.810 align:middle line:84%
if I want to say I have a
lot of assets, I'm rich,

00:15:44.810 --> 00:15:47.870 align:middle line:84%
the way that I talk about it
is if I were like these banks,

00:15:47.870 --> 00:15:51.690 align:middle line:84%
I could valuate my
kitty litter box

00:15:51.690 --> 00:15:57.979 align:middle line:84%
is a million dollars because my
mathematical models say it is.

00:15:57.979 --> 00:16:00.020 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: You're creating
the mathematical model.

00:16:00.020 --> 00:16:02.960 align:middle line:84%
>>ZEUS: Exactly, and my
created mathematical model

00:16:02.960 --> 00:16:05.930 align:middle line:84%
and its circular
logic reinforces

00:16:05.930 --> 00:16:08.690 align:middle line:84%
this supposedly independent
valuation of my kitty litter

00:16:08.690 --> 00:16:09.490 align:middle line:90%
box.

00:16:09.490 --> 00:16:12.745 align:middle line:84%
And what I have in
the book is, you know,

00:16:12.745 --> 00:16:14.710 align:middle line:84%
imagine me being
able to do that.

00:16:14.710 --> 00:16:17.150 align:middle line:84%
This is mark to fantasy,
or mark to model,

00:16:17.150 --> 00:16:18.510 align:middle line:90%
my mathematical model.

00:16:18.510 --> 00:16:21.860 align:middle line:84%
And then I take that and
leverage that another 100-fold

00:16:21.860 --> 00:16:25.140 align:middle line:84%
or 1,000-fold to buy up a
multi-billion-dollar dollar

00:16:25.140 --> 00:16:27.280 align:middle line:90%
company.

00:16:27.280 --> 00:16:29.182 align:middle line:84%
And then if I deal with
private equity firms,

00:16:29.182 --> 00:16:31.390 align:middle line:84%
then I will just try to
hollow it out and get as much

00:16:31.390 --> 00:16:34.610 align:middle line:84%
out of it as I can and then let
it go bankrupt and walk away.

00:16:34.610 --> 00:16:41.770 align:middle line:84%
And it's outrageous that,
purely on my say so, I can say,

00:16:41.770 --> 00:16:45.330 align:middle line:84%
all those houses out there that
have just got foreclosed upon

00:16:45.330 --> 00:16:48.460 align:middle line:84%
are still as high,
maybe even higher,

00:16:48.460 --> 00:16:51.210 align:middle line:84%
than they were at the
peak of the market.

00:16:51.210 --> 00:16:54.890 align:middle line:84%
And I don't want to come to
terms with taking a loss,

00:16:54.890 --> 00:16:58.210 align:middle line:84%
so I simply just say,
I assess it at this.

00:16:58.210 --> 00:17:00.920 align:middle line:84%
And that's what it is,
according to our models.

00:17:00.920 --> 00:17:05.619 align:middle line:84%
And our portfolio is still
as healthy as it's ever been,

00:17:05.619 --> 00:17:07.480 align:middle line:84%
even though it has
no relationship

00:17:07.480 --> 00:17:08.990 align:middle line:90%
whatsoever to the market.

00:17:08.990 --> 00:17:11.780 align:middle line:84%
And there's no one forcing
them to have any kind

00:17:11.780 --> 00:17:13.060 align:middle line:90%
of relationship to the market.

00:17:13.060 --> 00:17:16.750 align:middle line:84%
Now I'm sensitive to plunging
prices bringing it well

00:17:16.750 --> 00:17:19.107 align:middle line:84%
below its market value,
so I have suggested

00:17:19.107 --> 00:17:20.190 align:middle line:90%
something very reasonable.

00:17:20.190 --> 00:17:23.069 align:middle line:84%
I've said, bring it to
the inflation index.

00:17:23.069 --> 00:17:24.740 align:middle line:84%
In other words, draw
that little dotted

00:17:24.740 --> 00:17:28.230 align:middle line:84%
line of where the average
house prices have been,

00:17:28.230 --> 00:17:30.250 align:middle line:84%
and then bring it
down to that line.

00:17:30.250 --> 00:17:32.920 align:middle line:84%
You know, so then you can't
claim that you've been shorted,

00:17:32.920 --> 00:17:34.780 align:middle line:84%
and you're going
well below that.

00:17:34.780 --> 00:17:36.110 align:middle line:90%
But they don't do that.

00:17:36.110 --> 00:17:39.830 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: No, nothing in it
for them, like massive profits,

00:17:39.830 --> 00:17:42.380 align:middle line:90%
OK, number six is toxic assets.

00:17:42.380 --> 00:17:44.150 align:middle line:84%
>>ZEUS: Right, this
is a special, like,

00:17:44.150 --> 00:17:47.650 align:middle line:84%
[GROANING] of mine
because the term,

00:17:47.650 --> 00:17:52.020 align:middle line:84%
toxic assets, itself is an
inherently incoherent term.

00:17:52.020 --> 00:17:55.280 align:middle line:84%
Nothing that is an
asset can be toxic.

00:17:55.280 --> 00:17:58.300 align:middle line:90%
Toxics are 100% liability.

00:17:58.300 --> 00:18:00.420 align:middle line:90%
Assets are 100% benefit.

00:18:00.420 --> 00:18:02.960 align:middle line:84%
You can't stick
those two together.

00:18:02.960 --> 00:18:06.700 align:middle line:84%
So how did we ever come up
with this term, toxic asset,

00:18:06.700 --> 00:18:08.696 align:middle line:90%
as a meaningful term?

00:18:08.696 --> 00:18:11.280 align:middle line:90%


00:18:11.280 --> 00:18:12.440 align:middle line:90%
That's a good question.

00:18:12.440 --> 00:18:15.800 align:middle line:84%
I know what it serves
for these people.

00:18:15.800 --> 00:18:20.180 align:middle line:84%
It serves to have
these companies deny

00:18:20.180 --> 00:18:22.910 align:middle line:84%
their accountability
and responsibility.

00:18:22.910 --> 00:18:27.140 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Is it like these toxic
assets just happen to them?

00:18:27.140 --> 00:18:28.302 align:middle line:90%
>>ZEUS: Yes, yes.

00:18:28.302 --> 00:18:30.510 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And that's how
they position it or spin it.

00:18:30.510 --> 00:18:33.350 align:middle line:84%
>>ZEUS: I think that's
how they position it.

00:18:33.350 --> 00:18:35.620 align:middle line:84%
And then, of course, they
blame it on the little guy.

00:18:35.620 --> 00:18:38.470 align:middle line:84%
Oh, these people were
defaulting on their mortgage

00:18:38.470 --> 00:18:40.770 align:middle line:84%
so that infected the
mortgage-backed securities

00:18:40.770 --> 00:18:42.360 align:middle line:84%
and all the derivatives
that we have.

00:18:42.360 --> 00:18:44.480 align:middle line:84%
And now those aren't
worth anything.

00:18:44.480 --> 00:18:46.810 align:middle line:84%
And it's really, you
know, the little people

00:18:46.810 --> 00:18:49.650 align:middle line:84%
who overextended themselves
that created the problem

00:18:49.650 --> 00:18:51.450 align:middle line:90%
and made these toxic.

00:18:51.450 --> 00:18:54.350 align:middle line:84%
What happened, though, in
reality, is they leveraged.

00:18:54.350 --> 00:18:55.830 align:middle line:90%
They multiplied.

00:18:55.830 --> 00:18:59.290 align:middle line:84%
We could have easily paid
off the entire mortgage

00:18:59.290 --> 00:19:02.790 align:middle line:84%
of every person in
default in the biggest

00:19:02.790 --> 00:19:06.230 align:middle line:84%
default in this country's
history for about $1 trillion.

00:19:06.230 --> 00:19:08.320 align:middle line:84%
And instead, we spent
about $12 trillion

00:19:08.320 --> 00:19:11.726 align:middle line:84%
bailing these guys
out, $12 trillion.

00:19:11.726 --> 00:19:13.350 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: That's what
ticks people off.

00:19:13.350 --> 00:19:15.730 align:middle line:84%
>>ZEUS: Because they
multiplied them, right?

00:19:15.730 --> 00:19:18.580 align:middle line:84%
That toxicity could not have
been created by the little guy.

00:19:18.580 --> 00:19:21.050 align:middle line:84%
Otherwise, its maximum
would have been $1 trillion

00:19:21.050 --> 00:19:22.166 align:middle line:90%
to buy up every asset.

00:19:22.166 --> 00:19:24.040 align:middle line:84%
And you could have still
gotten at least 40%,

00:19:24.040 --> 00:19:26.302 align:middle line:84%
50%, 60% out of
that, so it would

00:19:26.302 --> 00:19:27.810 align:middle line:90%
have been than less than that.

00:19:27.810 --> 00:19:29.830 align:middle line:84%
But because they were
based in real assets,

00:19:29.830 --> 00:19:32.720 align:middle line:84%
they have some value, going
back to our original question.

00:19:32.720 --> 00:19:35.910 align:middle line:84%
But when you start spinning it
out into its imaginary value,

00:19:35.910 --> 00:19:38.740 align:middle line:84%
now you've got
nothing but toxins

00:19:38.740 --> 00:19:41.650 align:middle line:84%
being created by
the finance industry

00:19:41.650 --> 00:19:45.580 align:middle line:84%
and not taking
responsibility for it.

00:19:45.580 --> 00:19:51.450 align:middle line:84%
So this accountability,
explaining

00:19:51.450 --> 00:19:53.100 align:middle line:84%
this about toxic
assets, is to say, no.

00:19:53.100 --> 00:19:54.330 align:middle line:90%
It isn't you.

00:19:54.330 --> 00:19:55.990 align:middle line:84%
The toxins are
not being created,

00:19:55.990 --> 00:20:00.060 align:middle line:84%
even by irresponsible borrowing,
you know, hopeful borrowing.

00:20:00.060 --> 00:20:02.640 align:middle line:84%
And you're probably going to
have the consequence for that

00:20:02.640 --> 00:20:04.282 align:middle line:90%
anyway.

00:20:04.282 --> 00:20:07.940 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And explain what
you mean by hopeful borrowing.

00:20:07.940 --> 00:20:09.940 align:middle line:84%
>>ZEUS: Well, that's part
of the American ethic.

00:20:09.940 --> 00:20:11.970 align:middle line:84%
I mean, it's a part
of the American dream

00:20:11.970 --> 00:20:15.557 align:middle line:84%
that I have some problems with,
this notion of aspiration.

00:20:15.557 --> 00:20:17.140 align:middle line:84%
And you have a dream,
and you're going

00:20:17.140 --> 00:20:19.760 align:middle line:84%
to borrow against just
on a hope and a prayer.

00:20:19.760 --> 00:20:21.670 align:middle line:84%
And you want to live
the American dream.

00:20:21.670 --> 00:20:24.128 align:middle line:84%
And you want to have that house,
and maybe you don't really

00:20:24.128 --> 00:20:26.280 align:middle line:90%
have the money to pay for it.

00:20:26.280 --> 00:20:28.667 align:middle line:84%
But, you know, you're
going to get that job.

00:20:28.667 --> 00:20:32.000 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Right, that is part
of what it is to be an American,

00:20:32.000 --> 00:20:34.579 align:middle line:90%
is to dream the American dream.

00:20:34.579 --> 00:20:36.870 align:middle line:84%
>>ZEUS: Right, I'd like to
see that dream more in terms

00:20:36.870 --> 00:20:40.090 align:middle line:84%
of community interaction,
building up slowly,

00:20:40.090 --> 00:20:42.870 align:middle line:84%
if you want to start a business,
doing some pilot projects,

00:20:42.870 --> 00:20:46.070 align:middle line:84%
working out of your home,
learning the business,

00:20:46.070 --> 00:20:49.160 align:middle line:84%
being able to develop
it in a sustainable way,

00:20:49.160 --> 00:20:52.120 align:middle line:84%
knowing that it's filling an
actual need in the community,

00:20:52.120 --> 00:20:54.450 align:middle line:84%
right, rather than
a hope and a prayer.

00:20:54.450 --> 00:20:56.570 align:middle line:84%
You can pray all you
want, but it actually

00:20:56.570 --> 00:20:58.089 align:middle line:90%
helps something productive.

00:20:58.089 --> 00:21:00.630 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: You still have to take
the proper steps and action.

00:21:00.630 --> 00:21:02.320 align:middle line:90%
There's a process.

00:21:02.320 --> 00:21:04.380 align:middle line:84%
>>ZEUS: Yeah, and
so you're going

00:21:04.380 --> 00:21:08.540 align:middle line:84%
to see this kind of cropping
up again and again in the book

00:21:08.540 --> 00:21:09.820 align:middle line:90%
and in this.

00:21:09.820 --> 00:21:11.630 align:middle line:84%
American people have
allowed themselves

00:21:11.630 --> 00:21:16.340 align:middle line:84%
to be sold on this mentality
of getting rich quick, so they

00:21:16.340 --> 00:21:17.160 align:middle line:90%
have participated--

00:21:17.160 --> 00:21:18.410 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Well, we glorify it.

00:21:18.410 --> 00:21:20.550 align:middle line:84%
>>ZEUS: We glorify
it, and part of this

00:21:20.550 --> 00:21:23.490 align:middle line:84%
is to make us aware of
how we have actually

00:21:23.490 --> 00:21:24.940 align:middle line:90%
agreed to some of this stuff.

00:21:24.940 --> 00:21:26.600 align:middle line:84%
Now I'm not blaming
the victim here,

00:21:26.600 --> 00:21:30.707 align:middle line:84%
but there are ways in
which we bought it.

00:21:30.707 --> 00:21:33.290 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Well, yeah, if you can
buy a house that, as you say,

00:21:33.290 --> 00:21:36.260 align:middle line:84%
is more than 10 times
your yearly income

00:21:36.260 --> 00:21:42.650 align:middle line:84%
on an adjustable rate
mortgage right for 3% or 2%,

00:21:42.650 --> 00:21:43.640 align:middle line:90%
that's very tempting.

00:21:43.640 --> 00:21:45.190 align:middle line:90%
It's like, oh, my gosh.

00:21:45.190 --> 00:21:49.410 align:middle line:84%
I never thought I could have
a house like that, but I can.

00:21:49.410 --> 00:21:51.820 align:middle line:84%
And you just kind
of turn a blind eye

00:21:51.820 --> 00:21:54.980 align:middle line:84%
to what's going to happen in
three years or five years.

00:21:54.980 --> 00:21:57.430 align:middle line:84%
Well, I'm sure
something will happen.

00:21:57.430 --> 00:22:00.130 align:middle line:84%
I mean, I guess
we could sell it.

00:22:00.130 --> 00:22:02.180 align:middle line:84%
I guess we could sell
it if we get in trouble.

00:22:02.180 --> 00:22:03.480 align:middle line:90%
And a lot of people did that.

00:22:03.480 --> 00:22:05.400 align:middle line:84%
>>ZEUS: And everyone
was telling them,

00:22:05.400 --> 00:22:07.470 align:middle line:84%
these unscrupulous
mortgage lenders.

00:22:07.470 --> 00:22:09.440 align:middle line:84%
First of all, they were
having them sign up

00:22:09.440 --> 00:22:11.648 align:middle line:84%
for balloon payments, where
it would be low payments,

00:22:11.648 --> 00:22:14.280 align:middle line:90%
and then it would step up.

00:22:14.280 --> 00:22:16.330 align:middle line:90%
And they were giving loans.

00:22:16.330 --> 00:22:20.920 align:middle line:84%
I saw newspaper articles where
people making $45,000 a year

00:22:20.920 --> 00:22:24.642 align:middle line:84%
out in California were given
loans for a $745,000 house.

00:22:24.642 --> 00:22:25.600 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: That's crazy.

00:22:25.600 --> 00:22:27.150 align:middle line:84%
>>ZEUS: So we're
talking not even--

00:22:27.150 --> 00:22:29.320 align:middle line:84%
3 and 1/2 is what's
normal, 3 and 1/2 times

00:22:29.320 --> 00:22:30.220 align:middle line:90%
your yearly salary.

00:22:30.220 --> 00:22:33.120 align:middle line:84%
It was going up to 10 and even
exceeding that, all the way up

00:22:33.120 --> 00:22:35.420 align:middle line:90%
to almost 20.

00:22:35.420 --> 00:22:38.100 align:middle line:84%
And they didn't care
because the mortgage lenders

00:22:38.100 --> 00:22:39.310 align:middle line:90%
were going to get their fees.

00:22:39.310 --> 00:22:42.532 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Exactly, I assume you
saw the movie "The Big Short."

00:22:42.532 --> 00:22:43.490 align:middle line:90%
>>ZEUS: Oh, absolutely.

00:22:43.490 --> 00:22:45.865 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: A couple times, I
saw it a couple times anyway.

00:22:45.865 --> 00:22:47.120 align:middle line:90%
>>ZEUS: It was very well done.

00:22:47.120 --> 00:22:49.220 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Very well
done, and I thought

00:22:49.220 --> 00:22:53.580 align:middle line:84%
that the way they represented
that element of the crumbling

00:22:53.580 --> 00:22:57.990 align:middle line:84%
financial picture was beautiful
when they went to Florida.

00:22:57.990 --> 00:23:01.920 align:middle line:84%
And they talked to the guys
that were selling those loans.

00:23:01.920 --> 00:23:03.189 align:middle line:90%
And the guys would say, hey.

00:23:03.189 --> 00:23:04.480 align:middle line:90%
They don't know any difference.

00:23:04.480 --> 00:23:06.605 align:middle line:84%
In fact, we try to get
as many foreign people

00:23:06.605 --> 00:23:07.480 align:middle line:90%
on board as possible.

00:23:07.480 --> 00:23:10.080 align:middle line:84%
They don't understand the
language all that well.

00:23:10.080 --> 00:23:11.740 align:middle line:84%
I mean, it was
really despicable,

00:23:11.740 --> 00:23:14.065 align:middle line:84%
and there was no conscience
surrounding it at all.

00:23:14.065 --> 00:23:16.190 align:middle line:84%
And, of course, Florida
was one of the first states

00:23:16.190 --> 00:23:17.355 align:middle line:90%
to start going belly up.

00:23:17.355 --> 00:23:19.250 align:middle line:84%
I mean, the value
of their properties

00:23:19.250 --> 00:23:21.230 align:middle line:90%
dropped like a stone.

00:23:21.230 --> 00:23:26.290 align:middle line:84%
You could practically get
them for an annual salary.

00:23:26.290 --> 00:23:28.910 align:middle line:84%
>>ZEUS: They were
dropping 80%, 90%.

00:23:28.910 --> 00:23:29.770 align:middle line:90%
You could.

00:23:29.770 --> 00:23:32.186 align:middle line:84%
You could get them for almost
one times your annual salary

00:23:32.186 --> 00:23:33.090 align:middle line:90%
at a certain point.

00:23:33.090 --> 00:23:35.650 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Yeah, and
so anyway, if someone

00:23:35.650 --> 00:23:38.150 align:middle line:84%
hasn't seen "The Big Short,"
I think it's definitely worth

00:23:38.150 --> 00:23:45.520 align:middle line:84%
watching because it shows the
not hyperactive megalomania,

00:23:45.520 --> 00:23:49.390 align:middle line:84%
the psychology behind how
this became the way it did.

00:23:49.390 --> 00:23:51.862 align:middle line:84%
And by the way, on
that note for those

00:23:51.862 --> 00:23:53.320 align:middle line:84%
who have seen "The
Big Short," what

00:23:53.320 --> 00:23:55.450 align:middle line:84%
did you think of the
prime character in it

00:23:55.450 --> 00:23:59.250 align:middle line:84%
who was just looking at the
numbers and what he did?

00:23:59.250 --> 00:24:01.584 align:middle line:84%
Explain that to the people
so when they go see this film

00:24:01.584 --> 00:24:03.250 align:middle line:84%
they're looking at
it through your lens.

00:24:03.250 --> 00:24:06.020 align:middle line:84%
>>ZEUS: Well, he's kind of like
an interesting Shakespearean

00:24:06.020 --> 00:24:06.820 align:middle line:90%
character.

00:24:06.820 --> 00:24:09.730 align:middle line:84%
He's almost like the
narrator of a drama.

00:24:09.730 --> 00:24:12.010 align:middle line:84%
He's the guy kind
of behind the scenes

00:24:12.010 --> 00:24:16.164 align:middle line:84%
who understands that
the system is rigged,

00:24:16.164 --> 00:24:17.830 align:middle line:84%
and he understands
what the consequences

00:24:17.830 --> 00:24:20.849 align:middle line:84%
will be if they play out in the
direction that they're going.

00:24:20.849 --> 00:24:21.890 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Christian Bale.

00:24:21.890 --> 00:24:22.690 align:middle line:90%
>>ZEUS: Yes.

00:24:22.690 --> 00:24:24.970 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Yes, and he's
just about numbers.

00:24:24.970 --> 00:24:26.400 align:middle line:90%
>>ZEUS: Yeah, or was it Gosling?

00:24:26.400 --> 00:24:27.900 align:middle line:84%
Were you talking
about Gosling, too?

00:24:27.900 --> 00:24:28.950 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: No, Gosling
is the narrator--

00:24:28.950 --> 00:24:31.283 align:middle line:84%
>>ZEUS: OK, that's who I
thought you were talking about.

00:24:31.283 --> 00:24:33.980 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: No, Christian
Bale, the one who said, whoa.

00:24:33.980 --> 00:24:37.450 align:middle line:84%
We're going into a total
mass default on mortgages.

00:24:37.450 --> 00:24:38.420 align:middle line:90%
It's in the numbers.

00:24:38.420 --> 00:24:42.920 align:middle line:84%
And he was a quirky, Silicon
Valley kind of savant guy.

00:24:42.920 --> 00:24:47.790 align:middle line:84%
>>ZEUS: The savant, guy, OK,
right, and what I liked was--

00:24:47.790 --> 00:24:51.670 align:middle line:84%
and you don't really pick this
up explicitly in the movie.

00:24:51.670 --> 00:24:56.632 align:middle line:84%
But these guys who were
going contrary to--

00:24:56.632 --> 00:24:58.090 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: The credit
default swaps.

00:24:58.090 --> 00:25:00.626 align:middle line:84%
>>ZEUS: Yeah, who were going
contract to this, a lot of them

00:25:00.626 --> 00:25:02.250 align:middle line:84%
were activists and
agitators, realizing

00:25:02.250 --> 00:25:04.160 align:middle line:90%
that this was really unhealthy.

00:25:04.160 --> 00:25:06.030 align:middle line:84%
And they were going
to bet against this

00:25:06.030 --> 00:25:08.940 align:middle line:84%
because traditionally in the
financial market, if you bet

00:25:08.940 --> 00:25:11.000 align:middle line:84%
against it, you
can create a hedge

00:25:11.000 --> 00:25:13.070 align:middle line:84%
against irrational
exuberance, what's

00:25:13.070 --> 00:25:18.190 align:middle line:84%
called irrational exuberance,
from this testosterone-fuelled,

00:25:18.190 --> 00:25:22.190 align:middle line:84%
like, greed, because there
will be a consequence for it.

00:25:22.190 --> 00:25:25.740 align:middle line:84%
But what they realized, I
think, and he did as well,

00:25:25.740 --> 00:25:27.610 align:middle line:84%
at the end of the
movie when he realizes.

00:25:27.610 --> 00:25:29.202 align:middle line:90%
He put a number up on the board.

00:25:29.202 --> 00:25:30.160 align:middle line:90%
They kept losing money.

00:25:30.160 --> 00:25:31.720 align:middle line:90%
It was going down, like, 50%.

00:25:31.720 --> 00:25:33.240 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And everyone's saying,
you've got to do something.

00:25:33.240 --> 00:25:35.100 align:middle line:84%
>>ZEUS: Panicking, and at the
end it was almost like 500%.

00:25:35.100 --> 00:25:37.550 align:middle line:84%
I think it was like 496%
or something ridiculous.

00:25:37.550 --> 00:25:40.010 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Yeah, something
like that, 469%, something

00:25:40.010 --> 00:25:40.810 align:middle line:90%
like that, yeah.

00:25:40.810 --> 00:25:44.320 align:middle line:84%
>>ZEUS: Yes, and the other
one, played by Steve Carell,

00:25:44.320 --> 00:25:46.540 align:middle line:84%
they all realized though
they had gotten rich,

00:25:46.540 --> 00:25:48.360 align:middle line:90%
nothing had changed.

00:25:48.360 --> 00:25:49.940 align:middle line:90%
Absolutely nothing had changed.

00:25:49.940 --> 00:25:51.950 align:middle line:84%
These banks, they've
gotten away with it all.

00:25:51.950 --> 00:25:56.410 align:middle line:84%
The US taxpayers'
money backstopped them.

00:25:56.410 --> 00:26:00.470 align:middle line:84%
And their attempts
to correct the system

00:26:00.470 --> 00:26:03.860 align:middle line:84%
by betting against
it got them wealthy,

00:26:03.860 --> 00:26:07.300 align:middle line:84%
but it really didn't change
the underlying sickness.

00:26:07.300 --> 00:26:10.200 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: No, and
I bring this up

00:26:10.200 --> 00:26:11.900 align:middle line:84%
because it was so
well represented,

00:26:11.900 --> 00:26:14.640 align:middle line:84%
I think, toward what
you're speaking of.

00:26:14.640 --> 00:26:18.330 align:middle line:84%
Brad Pitt played the role of
a previously very successful

00:26:18.330 --> 00:26:20.890 align:middle line:84%
trader who was just
sick of the game.

00:26:20.890 --> 00:26:24.160 align:middle line:84%
He got out of the game and
moved to Boulder, Colorado,

00:26:24.160 --> 00:26:27.910 align:middle line:84%
grew his own organic vegetables,
you know, and all of that.

00:26:27.910 --> 00:26:30.520 align:middle line:84%
And in real life,
Brad Pitt is one

00:26:30.520 --> 00:26:35.920 align:middle line:84%
of the actors who has very
publicly come out and said,

00:26:35.920 --> 00:26:38.660 align:middle line:90%
that didn't buy me anything.

00:26:38.660 --> 00:26:41.140 align:middle line:84%
The fame, the
fortune, everything

00:26:41.140 --> 00:26:45.280 align:middle line:84%
I have bought me nothing by
way of happiness in my life.

00:26:45.280 --> 00:26:48.114 align:middle line:84%
And he was, I think, also one
of the producers or executive

00:26:48.114 --> 00:26:49.030 align:middle line:90%
producer of that film.

00:26:49.030 --> 00:26:49.140 align:middle line:90%
>>ZEUS: He was.

00:26:49.140 --> 00:26:50.400 align:middle line:90%
He was.

00:26:50.400 --> 00:26:53.530 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: So he's really trying
to-- he's using his position

00:26:53.530 --> 00:26:56.430 align:middle line:84%
to get this message out
that the system is sick.

00:26:56.430 --> 00:26:59.910 align:middle line:84%
>>ZEUS: Right, and I think that
that's where we are starting.

00:26:59.910 --> 00:27:01.410 align:middle line:84%
I mean, I hope that
when people read

00:27:01.410 --> 00:27:05.020 align:middle line:84%
this book and these documents,
which I will make available,

00:27:05.020 --> 00:27:06.950 align:middle line:90%
that they will get the notion.

00:27:06.950 --> 00:27:08.880 align:middle line:90%
They won't be overwhelmed.

00:27:08.880 --> 00:27:10.670 align:middle line:84%
They will be attracted
to the notion

00:27:10.670 --> 00:27:13.437 align:middle line:84%
that in very clear and
concise and simple terms

00:27:13.437 --> 00:27:15.020 align:middle line:84%
they have been able
to diagnose what's

00:27:15.020 --> 00:27:16.509 align:middle line:90%
at the heart of this sickness.

00:27:16.509 --> 00:27:18.300 align:middle line:84%
And that's why I liked
the film, because it

00:27:18.300 --> 00:27:21.560 align:middle line:84%
did a very personal,
well-edited job of getting

00:27:21.560 --> 00:27:23.560 align:middle line:90%
to the core of it.

00:27:23.560 --> 00:27:27.730 align:middle line:84%
And that's the first step
in making a healthy recovery

00:27:27.730 --> 00:27:30.640 align:middle line:90%
and finding alternatives.

00:27:30.640 --> 00:27:33.210 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Well, we're not even
done with the sick part yet.

00:27:33.210 --> 00:27:35.150 align:middle line:84%
>>ZEUS: Yeah, OK,
let's continue.

00:27:35.150 --> 00:27:37.220 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: OK,
sovereign governments

00:27:37.220 --> 00:27:39.830 align:middle line:84%
paying private central
banks to create money,

00:27:39.830 --> 00:27:42.260 align:middle line:84%
we'll kind of go on
through that quickly.

00:27:42.260 --> 00:27:44.130 align:middle line:84%
>>ZEUS: Right,
well, that's just--

00:27:44.130 --> 00:27:46.767 align:middle line:84%
I mean, the Federal Reserve
people don't understand.

00:27:46.767 --> 00:27:48.600 align:middle line:84%
They think it's a
governmental organization.

00:27:48.600 --> 00:27:49.000 align:middle line:90%
It's not.

00:27:49.000 --> 00:27:51.200 align:middle line:84%
It's a private organization,
and it represents

00:27:51.200 --> 00:27:52.400 align:middle line:90%
not the American people.

00:27:52.400 --> 00:27:55.640 align:middle line:84%
It represents the biggest
banks in the country.

00:27:55.640 --> 00:27:57.120 align:middle line:90%
And people don't know this.

00:27:57.120 --> 00:27:59.510 align:middle line:84%
When Hillary Clinton recently
said that the banks paid it

00:27:59.510 --> 00:28:03.760 align:middle line:84%
back in one of the debates,
they did not pay anything back.

00:28:03.760 --> 00:28:08.160 align:middle line:84%
They were given 0% money
in trillions of dollars,

00:28:08.160 --> 00:28:09.790 align:middle line:84%
many hundreds of
billions of dollars,

00:28:09.790 --> 00:28:11.770 align:middle line:84%
if not trillions of dollars,
from the Federal Reserve,

00:28:11.770 --> 00:28:13.040 align:middle line:90%
which is a private bank.

00:28:13.040 --> 00:28:14.840 align:middle line:84%
And they lent it back
to the US government

00:28:14.840 --> 00:28:17.100 align:middle line:90%
at 2% to 3% interest.

00:28:17.100 --> 00:28:19.610 align:middle line:84%
So the US government and
the American taxpayers

00:28:19.610 --> 00:28:25.560 align:middle line:84%
were paying these banks to give
them interest on the free money

00:28:25.560 --> 00:28:26.607 align:middle line:90%
that they got.

00:28:26.607 --> 00:28:28.690 align:middle line:84%
And so they are able to
get tens, if not hundreds,

00:28:28.690 --> 00:28:31.160 align:middle line:84%
of billions of dollars of
interest on that free money

00:28:31.160 --> 00:28:33.100 align:middle line:90%
they got to pay us back.

00:28:33.100 --> 00:28:34.520 align:middle line:84%
And where did they
get that money?

00:28:34.520 --> 00:28:35.390 align:middle line:90%
From us.

00:28:35.390 --> 00:28:37.870 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Yes, that was a
really fraudulent statement

00:28:37.870 --> 00:28:40.650 align:middle line:84%
on her part, but
she's known to be

00:28:40.650 --> 00:28:42.320 align:middle line:90%
in collusion with Wall Street.

00:28:42.320 --> 00:28:43.960 align:middle line:84%
>>ZEUS: Well, I mean,
I think that was

00:28:43.960 --> 00:28:47.140 align:middle line:84%
the criticism that was brought
up in the Sanders campaign.

00:28:47.140 --> 00:28:49.530 align:middle line:84%
When you are payed
enormous fees to speak--

00:28:49.530 --> 00:28:51.720 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: At least
$15 million thus far.

00:28:51.720 --> 00:28:53.719 align:middle line:84%
>>ZEUS: Yeah, your PAC
is receiving $15 million.

00:28:53.719 --> 00:28:56.110 align:middle line:84%
You're personally receiving
$600,000 from Goldman Sachs

00:28:56.110 --> 00:28:58.260 align:middle line:90%
alone to give three speeches.

00:28:58.260 --> 00:29:00.990 align:middle line:84%
You're more than a
little compromised.

00:29:00.990 --> 00:29:03.940 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: More than a
little compromised, yes, OK,

00:29:03.940 --> 00:29:07.370 align:middle line:84%
number four, "complex"
derivatives operating

00:29:07.370 --> 00:29:09.860 align:middle line:84%
as vehicles for fraud--
most people can't even

00:29:09.860 --> 00:29:12.200 align:middle line:90%
explain what derivatives are.

00:29:12.200 --> 00:29:14.490 align:middle line:84%
